    <!-- Catalog Description & Materials -->
    <h3 style="color:#002147; margin:16px 0 8px;">Catalog Description &amp; Materials</h3>
    <table role="table" style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin-bottom:18px;">
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#f3f6fa;">
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5; width:26%; color:#002147;"><strong>Catalog Course Description</strong></td>
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5;">
            BIO 137 Human Anatomy and Physiology I is an introduction to human anatomy and physiology. The interrelationship and structure and function of each body system in two semesters. The first semester will include basic chemistry, cell structure, cell physiology, metabolism, tissues, and integumentary, skeletal, muscular, and nervous systems.<br><br>
            The laboratory portion of BIO 137 is designed as a hands-on experience that corresponds to the lecture portion of the course. Anatomical models, computer programs, charts, slides of microscopic tissue sections, physiological experiments and preserved specimens for dissection will be used to reemphasize principles and structures discussed in lecture.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5; color:#002147;"><strong>Required Textbook</strong></td>
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5;">
            <em>Hole’s Human Anatomy &amp; Physiology</em> (2024 release). Charles J. Welsh; Cynthia Prentice-Carver. McGraw Hill. ISBN: 978-1-265-87040-9
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background:#f3f6fa;">
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5; color:#002147;"><strong>Course Materials</strong></td>
          <td style="padding:10px 12px; border:1px solid #d6dbe5;">
            The required course materials are provided via Blackboard, including the electronic textbook and Connect access. These resources are included in your tuition under the “Course Charge Model.” If you prefer a physical copy, a paper version of the textbook is available for optional purchase through the SCC bookstore.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

