    <!-- Policies & Information -->
    <h3 style="color:#002147; margin:20px 0 8px;">Policies &amp; Information</h3>

    <!-- Attendance Policy -->
    <h4 style="color:#002147; margin:12px 0 6px;">Attendance Policy</h4>
    <p>This is an in-person course. Attendance and participation in both lecture and laboratory are essential to your success.</p>
    <ul style="margin:6px 0 10px 18px; padding:0;">
      <li><strong>Lecture Attendance</strong>
        <ul style="margin:6px 0 6px 18px; padding:0;">
          <li>Students are expected to attend all lectures on time and prepared.</li>
          <li>If you must miss a lecture, communicate with the instructor in advance or as soon as reasonably possible. With timely communication, we can work together to keep you on track.</li>
          <li>Absences without communication make it difficult to support your progress. You are responsible for all material covered, announcements, and deadlines whether present or not.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Laboratory Attendance</strong>
        <ul style="margin:6px 0 6px 18px; padding:0;">
          <li>Attendance in lab is mandatory. Lab activities, quizzes, and exams are difficult to make up outside scheduled lab time.</li>
          <li>Students must complete the full lab session or assignment to receive credit. Arriving late or leaving early may result in no credit for that session.</li>
          <li>Because labs are hands-on and skill-based, consistent attendance is critical to mastering the material.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Think of attendance as a professional expectation. Just as in the workplace, showing up on time, being prepared, and communicating in advance when conflicts arise is part of your responsibility as a future health or science professional.</p>

    <!-- Communication Expectations -->
    <h4 style="color:#002147; margin:12px 0 6px;">Communication Expectations</h4>
    <ul style="margin:6px 0 10px 18px; padding:0;">
      <li>Communicate in a professional and timely manner, similar to expectations in a workplace.</li>
      <li>If you know you will miss class, notify the instructor before class begins by email.</li>
      <li>If an emergency arises, communicate as soon as reasonably possible.</li>
      <li>Simply notifying the instructor does not excuse an absence or missed work, but it demonstrates professionalism and may influence how flexibility is applied.</li>
      <li>Messages should be polite, clear, and specific (e.g., “I will be absent on Thursday due to [reason]. I understand lab quizzes cannot be made up. Will lecture notes be available?”).</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Withdrawal Policy -->
    <h4 style="color:#002147; margin:12px 0 6px;">Withdrawal Policy</h4>
    <ul style="margin:6px 0 10px 18px; padding:0;">
      <li>Withdraw by midterm (March 9) = W grade.</li>
      <li>After midterm (until Dec 3), withdrawal at instructor’s discretion.</li>
      <li>Instructor will not approve withdrawal if 20%+ of work has zeros.</li>
      <li>Official process through <strong>PeopleSoft</strong> required.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Academic Integrity -->
    <h4 style="color:#002147; margin:12px 0 6px;">Academic Integrity</h4>
    <p>Integrity means doing the right thing, even when nobody is looking. Please refer to the SCC Student Code of Conduct for more information regarding academic honesty and misconduct: <a href="https://somerset.kctcs.edu/current-students/academic-resources/code-of-conduct.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://somerset.kctcs.edu/current-students/academic-resources/code-of-conduct.aspx</a>.</p>

    <!-- Accessibility Services -->
    <h3 style="color:#002147; margin:20px 0 8px;">Accessibility Services for Students with Disabilities</h3>
    <p>SCC students with disabilities requiring accommodations (i.e. academic adjustment and/or auxiliary aids or services) for this course must contact the <a href="https://somerset.kctcs.edu/about/student-life/student-support-services/accessibility-services.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SCC Accessibility Services Office</a>. Please do not request accommodations directly from the instructor without a letter of accommodation from the Accessibility Services Office.</p>
    <p>The instructor is responsible for providing the designated reasonable accommodation(s) when notified by Accessibility Services. Upon receipt of the letter of accommodation, the instructor will contact the student to discuss how accommodations will be met. If your instructor has not contacted you and you have questions about your accommodations, you should contact your instructor as soon as possible.</p>
    <p>Students with a home college other than SCC must contact disability services at their home college for accommodations. The <a href="https://kctcs.edu/current-students/academic-resources/disability-services.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Accessibility Services Office at the student’s home college</a> will communicate with the student’s instructor and/or SCC’s Accessibility Services to coordinate and/or provide reasonable and appropriate accommodations to the student.</p>
    <p>In compliance with federal law, including the provisions of Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972, Sections 503 and 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 and the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990, SCC does not discriminate on the basis of race, sex, religion, color, national or ethnic origin, age, disability or military service in its programs, activities, admissions policies, scholarship and loan programs, athletic and other college-administered programs or employment. In addition, SCC does not discriminate on the basis of sexual orientation consistent with KCTCS nondiscrimination policy. Inquiries or comments regarding these issues should be directed to the SCC Accessibility Services Office, 808 Monticello Street, Somerset, KY 42501.</p>

